2.3.1. The boundary conditions

One cannot determine a well-posed set of boundary conditions to Eqs. (18) and (19) by inspection. A series of systematic developments for elastic shells [17, 18, 93] underlie the formulation of the general lipid membrane boundary conditions [50–52, 94, 95]. In what follows, we highlight possible boundary conditions and provide their physical justification. Details of our own derivations, which reproduce earlier results, are provided in Ch.V §5(d) of Ref. [53].
The in-plane equations governing lipid flows (18) are identical to those governing a twodimensional Newtonian fluid [96]. We thus expect the boundary conditions to be similar to those of a fluid, in which one specifies either the velocity v or (for a surface) the force per length F on the boundary. For general 2D materials, the force per length on the patch boundary is given by

